2001", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC3162.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document specifies the operation of RADIUS (Remote Authentication Dial In User Service) when run over IPv6 as well as the RADIUS attributes used to support IPv6 network access. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC3162;
  RFC4818 [label="RFC4818
RADIUS Delegated-IPv6-Prefix Attribute
2007", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4818.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document defines a RADIUS (Remote Authentication Dial In User Service) attribute that carries an IPv6 prefix that is to be delegated to the user.  This attribute is usable within either RADIUS or Diameter. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC4818;
  RFC6106 [label="RFC6106
IPv6 Router Advertisement Options for
DNS Configuration
2010", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6106.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document specifies IPv6 Router Advertisement options to allow IPv6 routers to advertise a list of DNS recursive server addresses and a DNS Search List to IPv6 hosts. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC6106;
  RFC4191 [label="RFC4191
Default Router Preferences and More-
Specific Routes
2005", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4191.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes an optional extension to Router Advertisement messages for communicating default router preferences and more-specific routes from routers to hosts.  This improves the ability of hosts to pick an appropriate router, especially when the host is multi-homed and the routers are on different links.  The preference values and specific routes advertised to hosts require administrative configuration; they are not automatically derived from routing tables. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC4191;
  RFC3633 [label="RFC3633
IPv6 Prefix Options for Dynamic Host
Configuration Protocol (DHCP) version 6
2003", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC3633.html", target="_top", tooltip="The Prefix Delegation options provide a mechanism for automated delegation of IPv6 prefixes using the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).  This mechanism is intended for delegating a long-lived prefix from a delegating router to a requesting router, across an administrative boundary, where the delegating router does not require knowledge about the topology of the links in the network to which the prefixes will be assigned."];
  cites -> RFC3633;
